ch collection, you will find diverse genres, including poetry, chant, fiction, creative nonfiction, and playwriting. The pieces are composed predominantly in English; however, the opening chant is in the CHamoru language (with translation by the author), other pieces are multilingual, and one poem is composed in CHamoru creole English. The themes range from genealogy to identity, colonialism to cultural revitalization, ecological connection to environmental injustice, love to sexual abuse, and belonging to diaspora. This anthology will introduce readers to the Mariana archipelago and the vibrancy of CHamoru literature, culture, histories, migrations, politics, memories, traumas, and dreams.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChamorro literature. 0aChamorro poetry. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Australian & Oceanian.2bisacsh  aAnthology.  aCHamoru.  aChamoru.  aGuam.  aOceania.  aOceanic Literature.1 aAnderson, Zachary FR, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Zachary Fr, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArnold, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamacho, Jacob L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamacho, Jacob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChargualaf Taimanglo, Tanya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrisostomo, Randizia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelgado, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Humlåo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Evelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHattori, Mary Therese Perez, econtributor.4ctb4ht